The paper deals with a combination of two declarative frameworks, answer set programming and fuzzy logic, to model reasoning by default over imprecise information. This makes it likely to belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) category. The paper also discusses the translation of FASP programs into satisfiability modulo theories (SMT), which is related to logic and automated reasoning, making it likely to belong to the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) category. The paper also deals with the structural properties of FASP programs, which can be related to programming languages and compilers, making it likely to belong to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) category. The paper also discusses the complexity of eliminating certain connectives, which can be related to algorithms and data structures, making it likely to belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) category. Finally, the paper presents and evaluates a prototype system, which can be related to machine learning and pattern recognition, making it likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) category.
